        			<translation>
        				The virtue of being unable to stay in one place. The art of being unable to produce in one place.	<!-- CG: I am not confident about this. The first sentence is taken from Lucan, and I tried to have it make sense here. -->
        				The more penetrating the art, the more intolerant of delay, especially like the art of Caesar, Sallust, Tacitus.
        				To which the related art of Virgil in the Aeneid, Ovid in the Metamorphosis, Seneca in the Tragedies.
        				Art is as readily flowing, as prudence is the most vigorous of all things. 	<!-- CG: I have no idea what this means. I assume 'ars' is understood for the adjective?-->
        				O judgment rich in proof. O divine and winged speed of thoughts. Only an adamantine style.
        			</translation>
